        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>VY CMa is one of the most molecular rich evolved stars known. To study the dust emission in Band 3 we must be able to successfully separate the continuum emission from the molecular line emission. Therefore we cannot use the standard continuum mode and instead we use the spectral line mode. 

The line widths will be between 40 and 70 km s-1 and so our spectral resolution of ~3.5 km s-1 will provide us with at least 10 spectral resolution elements across all lines.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>In Band 3 we wish to image the dust continuum with either 130 or sub-130 mas spatial resolution, respectively. This resolution is required to study the dust clumps C and VY from O'Gorman et al. (2015) in similar detail at this lower frequency. The ALMA SV data also showed that the overall dust structure is relatively compact (&lt;0.6" in diameter) so we will not resolve-out any of this dust. If different spatial resolution is achieved in Bands 3 and 6, then we convolve the higher spatial resolution image with the beam from the lower to obtain an accurate spectral index map.

Using the IRAM interferometer on Plateau de Bure, Lucas et al. (1992) found the extent of the 28SiO(v=0,J=2-1) emission to be less than 3arcsec. In fact, Shinnaga et al. (2003) imaged the 28SiO(v=0, J=1-0) line with the Very Large Array and found the emission to be compact (&lt;0.6" in diameter)and clumpy. Therefore, it is likely that we do not resolve-out any of the SiO(v=0,2-1) emission.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our main target line in this science goal is the SiO(v=0, 2-1) thermal line. Lucas et al. (1992)  found this line to be 70 km s-1 in width. At 3 km s-1 spectral resolution this line had a peak flux density of 15 Jy. The source was unresolved and their beam size was 2.4 x 2.2 arcseconds. Conservatively assuming the SiO to be uniform over this beam (even though Shinnaga et al. (2003) has shown the SiO(v=0,1-0) emission is more compact) we find a peak flux of 30mJy/beam. We aim for a 30sigma sensitivity limit for the peak line flux. We therefore need to reach a sensitivity of 1.0 mJy/beam. In 1.57 hours we can achieve this sensitivity at a spectral resolution of 7 km s-1. This provides us with 10 resolution elements across the line. More resolution elements will be achievable or higher S/N per element should the SiO(v=0,2-1) line be more compact like the SiO(v=0,1-0) emission.

ALMA Science Verification data allows robust predictions to be made for the flux density of the dust continuum. To be conservative we assume a spectral index of 2.7 (it is possible that the dust is still be optically thick in which case the spectral index would be 2) and extrapolate our Band 7 flux values from O'Gorman (2015). The estimated peak dust continuum flux is 4.5 mJy/beam and so the S/N of the dust image will be about 270. Hence, we will also obtain a high-dynamic-range dust continuum map. 

</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We have applied a spectral averaging of 2 to reduce the data rate in all 4 basebands. This worsens the spectral resolution only by a small margin, i.e., from ~3 to 3.5 km s-1 and will not affect the analysis of lines. The data rate is 12.21 MB/s, still slightly above the policy value of 12.0 MB/s. However, some lines are expected to be only about 40 km s-1 in width so we do not want to spectral average further, as this would reduce the possibilities with the scientific analysis.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_HIGH_DATA_RATE</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
