        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our main target line in this science goal is the SiO(v=0, 5-4) thermal line. Tenenbaum et al (2010) found this line to be 60 km s-1 in width. At 2.8 km s-1 spectral resolution this line had a peak flux density of 35 Jy/beam. The source was unresolved and their beam size was 30 x 30 arcseconds. However, interferometric studies show the lower energy lines (SiO(2-1) and SiO(1-0))to be compact (&lt;2arcsec) so we conservatively assume the SiO(5-4) emisison to be uniform over the beam of Lucas et al. (1992) (who found the SiO(2-1) line to be unresolved with their 2.4 arcsecond beam). We find a peak flux of 64 mJy per ALMA beam. We aim for a 30sigma detection for for the peak line flux. This may be higher if the SiO emission is more compact or clumped. We therefore need to reach a sensitivity of 2.1 mJy/beam. In 35.31 minutes (including overheads) we can achieve this sensitivity at a spectral resolution of 2.7 km s-1. This provides us with 20 resolution elements across the line. More resolution elements will be achievable or higher S/N per channel, should the SiO(v=0,5-4) line be more compact.

Our ALMA SV analysis allows robust predictions to be made for the flux density of the dust continuum. To be conservative we assume a spectral index of 2.7 (it is possible that the dust is still be optically thick in which case the spectral index would be 2) and extrapolate our Band 7 flux values from O'Gorman (2015). The estimated peak dust continuum flux is 70 mJy per ALMA beam and so the S/N of the dust image will be excellent and probably dynamic range limited. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
    </prj:ScienceGoal>
