    <prp:abstract>VY Canis Majoris is an extreme oxygen-rich red supergiant with an exceptionally dust and molecular rich cicumstellar environment. This makes it an ideal laboratory for studying the unknown mass-loss mechanism in red supergiants and the dust formation process in evolved stars. 

Our team has been heavily involved in the reduction and analysis of recent high frequency (Band 9 and Band 7) ALMA Science Verification data. The dusty continuum was imaged in spectacular detail and revealed that the star has being undergoing anisotropic mass loss over the past few decades. Remarkably, most of the dust is contained in a massive dust clump located at least at 60 stellar radii.

Here we propose similar spatial resolution lower frequency (Band 3 and Band 6) observations of this dust forging factory. The continuum emission will reveal the mass, composition and potentially proper motion of the massive dust clump, while molecular lines will study the efficiency of gas depletion by condensing onto grains for potentially important seed molecules.</prp:abstract>
